[normal]Written evidence submitted by the National Union of Journalists[bold] (NUJ)[bold] [FBB0079][bold]&#xa0;[bold]What should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]How well has th[bold]e BBC performed in the current c[bold]harter period in achieving i[bold]ts mission and public purposes? [bold]Are the [bold]public pur[bold]poses in the current c[bold]harter the right ones? How m[bold]ay[bold] they change?[bold]What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? [bold]What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]How have the BBC’s commercial[bold] activities during the current c[bold]harter fitted with the BBC’s public purpo[bold]ses and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale[bold] of such activities beyond [bold]2016.[bold]What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?[bold]How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016? Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond t[bold]he BBC?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?  [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
